PART-1

# htpasswd -c -B -b </path/to/users.htpasswd> <username> <password>
IF I NEED TO ADD ANOTHER USER THEN I NEED TYPE THIS COMMAND:::------->>>>>>>>>>>>.
####  htpasswd -B -b </path/to/users.htpasswd> <username> <password>  

FOR EXAMPLE:::---->>>
# htpasswd -c -B -b user-details.txt(it could be anything) <username>/ bibek  <password>/ redhat@123

(((((    Use the -c option only when creating a file. The -c option replaces all file content if
the file already exists.)))))

FOR EXAMPLE:::---->>>
# htpasswd -B -b user-details.txt(it could be anything) <username>/ bibek-01  <password>/ redhat@123

PART-2  
Creating HTPASWD secret:::::------------->>>>

# oc create secret generic htpass-secret --from-file=htpasswd=<path_to_users.htpasswd> -n openshift-config 
///// oc create secret generic htpass-secret --from-file=htpasswd=<path_to_users.htpasswd> -n openshift-config

## oc edit secret/htpass-secret   hit enter
## oc extract secret/htpass-secret -to=-

#####   oc create secret generic htpass-secret --from-file=htpasswd=<path_to_users.htpasswd> /user-details.txt -n openshift-config ######
### echo "password in the secret file" | base64 -d

PART-3 
NOW LET'S CONFIURE OAUTH AUTHENTICATION:::::::--------------------->>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
## oc get oauth
## oc get oauth/cluster

FOR BACKUP::>>
## oc get oauth/cluster -oyaml > oauth-backup.yaml
## oc edit oauth OR  ## oc edit oauth/cluster 
##  oc get secret -n openshift-config
AFTER THAT WE NEED ADD THE IDENTITY-PROVIDER TO THE {{ oauth/cluster }}
{{{{{{{   Main Purpose of openshift-config

The namespace is used for storing:
 Identity provider configuration

HTPasswd secret

LDAP certificates

GitHub OAuth secrets

OAuth client secrets}}}}}}}}}


## watch oc get po -n openshift-authentication

{{{{{{{{{ 1. oauth-openshift pods

These pods implement the OAuth server for OpenShift.
They handle:

Login pages
Identity provider flows (HTPasswd, LDAP, GitHub, Google, etc.)
Token requests
Logout requests.

2. authentication-operator pod

Ensures OAuth server is running correctly.
Watches changes in the openshift-config namespace.
Reconciles OAuth configuration continuously.}}}}}}}}}}}



WORNGLY I DELETED THE user.detail.txt FILE ::::------>>>>>
NO PROBLEM

1. FIRST LOGIN TO THE OPENSHIFT-CONFIG  NAMESPACE ::-->>>>>>>>>>>

## oc project openshift-config
## oc get secret
THEN THERE WILL BE HTPASS-SECRET FILE 
## oc extract secret/htpass-secret --to=- ( to read only , if i don't wwant to read this file then,,,,,,)
## oc extract secret/htpass-secret --to=. 
## cat htpasswd

2. AFTER THAT WE CAN CREATE USER :::--->>>>>>>>>>

## htpasswd -B -b htpasswd(it could be anything) <username>/ bibek-02  <password>/ redhat@123
## htpasswd -B -b htpasswd(it could be anything) <username>/ bibek-03  <password>/ redhat@123

3. THEN WE NEED TO UPDATE THE SECRET FILE ::----->>>>>>>>>>

## oc set data secret/htpass-secret  --from-file=htpasswd=htpasswd (( THIS COMMAND WHEN WE ARE INSIDE OPENSHIFT-CONFIG ))
,,,IF YOU ARE NOT INSIDE  OPENSHIFT-CONFIG THEN
## oc set data secret/htpass-secret  --from-file=htpasswd=htpasswd -n openshift-config

4. DELETING USER ::::----->>>>

# htpasswd -D <FILE> htpasswd <USERNAME> bibek-03 

5.THEN WE NEED TO UPDATE SECRET-FILE ::::---------->>>>>>>>>

## oc set data secret/htpass-secret  --from-file=htpasswd=htpasswd 
## oc get users
## oc delete users bibek-03
## oc get identity
## oc delete identity J2C-users:bibek-03

